# DATA CLEANING
df.info()
# is used to get a comprehensive technical summary of a pandas DataFrame.
#It provides an instant health check of your dataset by showing its size, data types, and memory usage.
#When you run df.info(), pandas prints out a structured summary containing five key pieces of information:Total Index Range: The total number of rows and their index labels (e.g., RangeIndex: 5000 entries, 0 to 4999).Column Names: A complete list of all columns in the dataset.Non-Null Counts: The number of non-missing values in each column. This helps you instantly spot missing data (NaN values).Data Types (dtypes): The technical format of each column (e.g., int64 for whole numbers, float64 for decimals, object for text).Memory Usage: Exactly how much computer RAM the dataset is consuming.
# Why do data analysts use it?Spotting Missing Data: By comparing the column counts to the total entries, you know exactly which columns need cleaning.Debugging Data Types: Checking if a column that should be numbers (like Salary) was accidentally loaded as text (object) due to a typo in the raw file.Optimising Performance: Watching the memory footprint when working with huge production datasets.
